com:
***READ THE GUIDE***

THE GUIDE: http://gunpla.buyfags.moe/

***READ THE GUIDE***

For those new to gunpla/plamo or even just new to this thread; please read the guide. Please read it before asking questions, as there is a chance it has already been answered there.

For those unfamiliar, "plamo" is a shortened form of "plastic model". If it's made of plastic, someone can probably help you here!
If you're new, you're gonna fuck up. Don't worry! If you're experienced, don't make the new people worry!

And remember to report any shitposting and spam to keep the thread clean and civil.

>Why won't anyone answer my question?
Try being specific, especially about your materials and process. Post images whenever possible; even if the kit/part looks bad, you are more likely to get help posting images.

>Why are my pictures sideways?
4chan strips EXIF data from images when they're uploaded to the site from your phone, including the orientation display tag. To fix this, save your images separately, or use an app that will rotate and save the images for you.
One commonly used app that works well on Android:
https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.simplemobilephotoresizer

>I don't pay attention to lyrics in any anime song,
You are absolutely retarded.
Anime OPs are 100% involved in the storytelling.
Not every single anime does it, but the VAST majority of them do. Just looking at the history of anime this should be clear, if you've seen anime made before 1985 you'll notice that quite a lot of them even had the name of the show being explicitly stated in the name.
https://youtu.be/wegtLnC5lyI
https://youtu.be/I4aQQBLokNo
https://youtu.be/b9TE3226T-g
Even American cartoons did this, if you can recall theme songs like power rangers or transformers you'll see what I mean.

The lyrics of modern anime OPs are less explicit and usually convey the tone or themes of the show in some way. Sometimes directly or vaguely like a poem.
This is why some writers/directors make it a point to always be involved in the direction of the OP. Tomino for example has writen the lyrics for the OPs of every show he has worked on.
Okouichi wrote the lyrics for the G-Witch OP and as the show has gone on its been revealed that certain plot points were hinted at in the OP.
All of Eureka Seven's OPs follow this rule as well.

Go back and look at your favorite shows and analyze their opening lyrics, you'll find that most of the time they relate to the show in some way. They're not just throwing random J-pop tracks on there.

I think it's mostly because the Alternative Company only uses Daughtress during the initial arc, so they didn't want the Vultures using even more Daughtress.

You have two unique Custom Jenices with line art, then the "generic" Jenice Kai, recolored Septem Kai and Octape Kai with their own line art. Meanwhile, you have the repainted Alternative Company Daughtress, Command and Cannon which appear a few times throughout the first arc, so there were quite a few of them.

There were Daughtress Kai during episode 2 though in some of the crowd scenes, but the Daughtress is outnumbered among other customs in those crowd scenes because there were 3 different SRA models for base, while only the Daughtress for the UNE. So, you get cases like pic related. The animators draw one of each model from the four suits they have for this scene, and the Daughthress ends up outnumbered. A similar logic happens with the Vultures Janmil asks for help during the battle against the Alternative Company. The Alternative Company is using custom Daughtress, so to avoid repetition you have one group with custom Jenices, another with Septems, another Octapes (number-wise, the Alternative company had more troops than any of the 3 vultures).

After you're done with these episodes though, you have Ennil's vulture group mostly using high mobility Daughtress, and later on Witz's town getting the custom Daughtress Tank for defense. >"X servers are dead / can't play with someone from a different region"
You can switch servers on the start screen.

>"What's the green currency"
Material Points, MP. You get them from duplicated loot box items.

>"How to get more shit without spending a dime besides the usual"
Standard Pass.
1000 CAPs: lvl 18, 58.
Tickets: lvl 8, 38, EX1-3.
If you save enough CAP you can unlock at least 2 MS.
Never use CAP for supply pod pulls, use the tickets instead, same drops.

>If the challenge is "Play/Win X matches" with specific suits. Does the entire match need to be played with that character alone?
No, you can pick whatever MS you need for your challenges for a short period of time then switch to one you actually want to play. It will count at the end of the match.

>"I want Char's Zaku skin"
This and the G-3 Gundam skin cost 4000 MP each (dupe coins).
Could vary between 100 to 400 USD (10k-40k EVO Coins).
5 MP for grey items; 50 for blue; 100 for purple; 200 for gold items.
Available until November 29.

>"I'm a third-worlder and Bandai doesn't love me"
1. Get a free VPN, any will do but TunnelBear is what has worked for several anons.
2. Set yourself in NA, download GunEvo from SteamDB. (https://steamdb.info/app/1816670/)
3. Once the download started, turn off the VPN. You don't need it anymore.
>"Muh illegal"
There's no purchase involved so it's not tax evasion, no one will care.

name: Anonymous
com:
Do you lads see Zambot 3 as a "true classic" or is it mostly a historical piece?
I lean more towards the latter. It has its moments (Killer the Butcher, human bomb arc, last 4 eps) but alot of the other episodes can be pretty anemic, especially during the first 9 episodes when the production staff were still trying to find their groove and the interesting/memorable elements hadn’t really kicked in. They also struggled making good robot fights, even the latter half had a few duds.

Definitely got the feeling that most of the buzz around this series comes down to it being interesting to look back upon (Sunrise’s first original, defined Tomino's career path, pulls a couple of genre conventions on their head), rather than being a well-made show in it’s own right.
”Impact over quality” is not a problem I have with ’70s anime as a whole, if anything there are quite a few that still stand strong on their own merits and aren’t as wooden in terms of direction (staging, lighting, editing/pacing, use of music, etc.).
>Yamato and Harlock blend fantastical space adventures with heavy subject matter in a very appealing way, with some great music and cinematic direction to boot (especially in Harlock), and the characters ain’t too shabby either. These two really feel like the pure platonic ideal of a space opera come to life, the greybeards who see them as ”the greatest TV cartoons ever made” ain’t too far off.
>Mazinger Z has alot of fun character interactions and devious ”master plans” to go with the iconic monsters
>Danguard Ace is a heartfelt father and son story, and the giant robot stuff doesn't disappoint either (have only seen the 2013 compilation films though)
>First Gundam did a good job in terms of forward momentum, while keeping the characters and battles interesting even during the less eventful episodes
All in all I wouldn’t say I’ve been ”cheated” of my time for watching Zambot, I’m just curious about it’s following.

name: Anonymous
com:
Previous thread: >>21277686

Let's discuss the best TV series of UC Gundam.
>Should I skip ZZ?
No! ZZ is essential viewing. The First Neo Zeon War is as important as any other conflict in UC history. You miss out on essential character development(Haman & Kamille/Fa, Minerva Zabi), fantastic mecha designs, best OP/ED songs in UC, lots of great new characters (Elpeo Ple, Ple Two, Chara Soon, Roux Louka) including Judau who is one of the best protagonists in Gundam.
>But /m/ told me Moon Moon ruins the show
Absolutely not. Moon Moon is important canon wise now with Moon Gundam being a thing.
>I'm still not convinced
Haman, Kamille, Fa, Bright Noa and other favourites are still there. ZZ is still referenced in newer UC titles showing it's importance and longevity.

com: Noob question here but do suits like the Borjanorn/Zaku or any thermonuclear powered suits leak radiation when damaged or destroyed? Do they become walking dirty bombs? If so how does the universe tackle the issue of contamination given thousands and thousands of these things have exploded all over earth? [{'no': 21326655, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)12:40:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21326611
It's a pretty big fireball. But it's nowhere near being as powerful as a atomic explosion. Again going off of BT lore for this.

Fusion reactor cores need to be under vacuum in order to get reliable fusion to occur. If reactor shielding is breached before safeties shut down the reactor. Gas will be sucked into the superhot reactor core and quickly expands. Resulting in a explosion that can rip some mechs in half. Along with creating a blinding fireball.

This does make me wonder how Minovsky reactors are constructed. As It's been shown that MS violently explode from reactor hits in space.', 'time': 1670521223, 'resto': 21325837}, {'no': 21327272, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)19:37:16', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21326655
https://gundam.fandom.com/wiki/Gundam_Wiki:Technology#Minovsky_Physics', 'time': 1670546236, 'resto': 21325837}, {'no': 21327275, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)19:39:30', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21327272
"According to the timeline deduced by the Gundam Officials, in UC 0071, Zeon researchers created the Minovsky ultracompact fusion reactor . Instead of the conventional magnetic field, this improved version of the Minovsky-Ionesco reactor used an I-field to confine and compress the reactor fuel, triggering a fusion reaction. The Minovsky particles produced as a byproduct of the helium-3 fusion reaction were recycled to keep that reaction going. The Minovsky particles that form the I-field lattice also helped catalyze the fusion reaction, in a process similar to the muon-catalyzed fusion investigated by real-world scientists during the 1950s. This super-efficient design was only a fifth as large as an equivalently powerful Minovsky-Ionesco reactor, allowing the reactor to be mounted within the mobile suit instead of an external backpack. For this reason, it was adopted for use on mobile suits as the standard power plant"', 'time': 1670546370, 'resto': 21325837}, {'no': 21327277, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)19:41:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21327275
Considering info provided Battletech may not be the best source of comparison for UC Minovsky fusion engines.', 'time': 1670546483, 'resto': 21325837}, {'no': 21327350, 'now': '12/08/22(Thu)20:28:07', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21326505

Yes, they decay within a few hours.The original plan as Tomino envisioned it in the production notes for the show was for Minovsky particles to last for a long time, and for a mix of Minovsky particles and radiation from early battles in the One Year War to have contaminated various Sides so badly that long range communication was impossible in much of the Earthpshere, but by the time the show aired it had obviously changed and Minovsky radiation in the show is generally depicted as a short term problem. You spread them before a battle, and then after a battle they dissipate naturally on their own, so characters talk about using radar or pick up long range transmissions, including TV signals regularly.

I say generally though because Garma does refer to a layer of Minovsky particles in the upper atmosphere, which implies it's long term. However, Sunrise have run with Minovsky particles being a short term thing, and there is mention of radar and use of long range comms in every UC show after the first show as well. I'm pretty sure they both happen in Char's Counterattack and F91 for that matter; not sure about the OVAs. Also, while I don't recall the source off hand I recall seeing a page from some data book or other that showed the spread of Minovsky particles from a ship and how long it'd last. I'm pretty sure I posted it in a thread here several years back, but christ knows how I'd find it now.', 'time': 1670549287, 'resto': 21325837}]

com: The eagerly anticipated Project G will be a 13-episode anime, titled New Grendizer! The Great Space War (新グレンダイザー! 宇宙大戦争!, Shin Gurendaizā! Uchūdaisensō!). Honorable mangaka Go Nagai, executive producer of this upcoming anime, wants to take full advantage of 3DCG technology, in this fully 3DCG anime. It will be a co-production by Toei Animation and GEMBA, with assistance from IXIXI. Set after the original mid-70s Grendizer anime, New Grendizer takes place on the newly restored Planet Fleed. It was peaceful in the Kingdom of Planet Fleed, until it was invaded by the massive spacefaring Yamata-no-Orochi from Uncle Go's Susano Oh ( 凄ノ王 Susano Ō). Sadly, not even Duke Fleed in the mighty Grendizer can save Planet Fleed from Orochi, as Orochi BTFO'd Grendizer and REKT Planet Fleed into an asteroid belt. Badly defeated by Orochi, the remnants of the Fleed Kingdom fled to earth, including Duke Fleed, who survived his encounter with Orochi thanks to a convenient escape pod. After the remnants of the Fleed Kingdom retreated to earth, they take refuge, and build a harder, bigger, faster, stronger Grendizer for Duke Fleed, the titular New Grendizer. Immediately afterwards, Duke Fleed and friends left earth. Thus began Duke Fleed's quest to hunt down Orochi, and avenge the destruction of Planet Fleed.

com:
Rank the Cutie Honey adaptations. Here's mine:

S-tier: New Cutie Honey. Great writing, great voice acting, full of interesting villains and guest characters. 10/10 face and tits on Honey here
Good tier: Flash & OG anime. Beautiful visuals on both. OG has all those trippy backgrounds while Flash really ramps up the drama by the end.
Meh tier: Re. Not a fan of retarded Honey and bulldyke Natsuko. All style over substance and apes way too much from the 70s anime, which is typical for Annoshit. Hoping the live-action is better.
Shit tier: Universe. Utter fucking garbage. Cheap ugly animation (esp that CGI dimension where all the fights go on) and Honey is a dumb fucking cunt throughout. Only 12 eps and it alrealy feels like a slog to finish

Also been meaning to check out Tears and The Live. Thought on those?

>What is Bibleman?
Bibleman is an American Christian-themed direct-to-video children's series created by Tony Salerno that ran from 1995 to 2010 to promote Christianity. The series centers around an evangelical superhero who fights evil, often by quoting scripture, as well as breaking the fourth wall. The show had three incarnations: The Bibleman Show, The Bibleman Adventure, and Bibleman: Powersource. The series' titular character was played by Willie Aames from 1995 to 2003 and by Robert T. Schlipp from 2004 to 2010. Originally owned by Pamplin Entertainment, then sold to Tommy Nelson, the series is currently owned by B&H Kids. It was re-launched in CGI format in 2016 (new title Bibleman: The Animated Adventures).

Nothing you said has anything to do with space. You are talking about battle choreography. There are plenty earthbound fights that are just guys shooting at each other. Gundam Wing had a ton of earth battles that were just stock footage of shooting.

The real problem that appears in space fights are usually when they take place in locations that are just nondescript black backgrounds.
It helps to have stuff in the background to create a sense of depth and geography within the battle space.
CCA does this really well with the final confrontation between Amuro and Char on Axis. Thunderbolt does this by using the space colony and debris as a visual anchor.

But this doesn't mean that black backgrounds == bad because there are also plenty of fights where that is the case but they still convey the 3D depth of a space well and have back-and-forth momentum.', 'time': 1670471909, 'resto': 21316643}, {'no': 21325648, 'now': '12/07/22(Wed)23:06:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>21325632
>But this doesn't mean that black backgrounds == bad
I'll disagree because it gives off the impression that the fight is taking place in deep space, away from anything, which is just pretty much never the case. The suits are always orbiting some planet or moon and showing it in the background is a good way to convey where you're supposed to be. In the case of UC fights, the size of the Earth or Moon on the background help show where the fight is taking place. If the battle just takes place in the void then there's nothing to tell me whether the fight is taking place on Earth, the Moon or any of the Lagrange Points/Sides. This is a problem with naval battles in media because the ocean looks the same to most people no matter where you go except there's nothing you can do in this case. In the case of space fights you should always have some sort of celestial body visible.', 'time': 1670472369, 'resto': 21316643}]

com:
***READ THE GUIDE***

THE GUIDE: http://gunpla.buyfags.moe/

***READ THE GUIDE***

For those new to gunpla/plamo or even just new to this thread; please read the guide. Please read it before asking questions, as there is a chance it has already been answered there.

For those unfamiliar, "plamo" is a shortened form of "plastic model". If it's made of plastic, someone can probably help you here!
If you're new, you're gonna fuck up. Don't worry! If you're experienced, don't make the new people worry!

And remember to report any shitposting and spam to keep the thread clean and civil.

>Why won't anyone answer my question?
Try being specific, especially about your materials and process. Post images whenever possible; even if the kit/part looks bad, you are more likely to get help posting images.

>Why are my pictures sideways?
4chan strips EXIF data from images when they're uploaded to the site from your phone, including the orientation display tag. To fix this, save your images separately, or use an app that will rotate and save the images for you.
One commonly used app that works well on Android:
https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.simplemobilephotoresizer

Links:
>A guide to other types of plamo:
http://www.mediafire.com/view/1vf1aw7v91pz5pa/Airfix%20Model%20World%20Specia%20-By-Step
